\begin_layout Plain Layout
Due to the nonexistence of analytical solutions of partial differential
 equations for most polygonal enclosures, we replicate a method used originally
 in the study of flexural vibrations of regular polygonal plates 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "liew_set_1991"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 To address the spectrum of the Dirac-Weyl equation in finite regions, we
 first review possible types of boundary conditions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "brey_electronic_2006,berry_michael_victor_neutrino_1987"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and generalize the polynomial method for two component spinors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
With this method, we obtain the low-energy eigensystem of Schrödinger’s
 equation in polygons with hard boundaries, which we compare to existing
 exact theoretical results and to numerical diagonalization of the Laplacian
 operator.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To address the spectrum of the Dirac-Weyl equation in finite regions, we
 first review possible types of boundary conditions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "brey_electronic_2006,berry_michael_victor_neutrino_1987"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and generalize the polynomial method for two component spinors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We were able to replicate an exact solution for a triangular flake with
 boundary conditions such as found in graphene zigzag edges 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "berry_michael_victor_neutrino_1987,gaddah_exact_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We found, however that this is a very special case, essentially equivalent
 to the solution of Schrödinger’s equation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We also studied hexagonal and square shaped flakes, with more general boundary
 conditions, which constitute a non-trivial generalization of the polynomial
 method for two component spinors.
