\begin_layout Subsection
One-Dimensional Toy-Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1$
\end_inset

, the Hamiltonian is
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "berry_neutrino_1987"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{K}} & \mathrm{\rightarrow\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{K}}+m\left(\vec{r}\right)\sigma_{z}}, & m\left(\vec{r}\right) & =\begin{cases}
0 & \mathrm{inside}\\
+\infty & \mathrm{outside}
\end{cases},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and the problem is exactly solvable in 1D, with spectrum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{n,\pm}=\pm\hbar v_{F}\left(2n+1\right)\frac{\pi}{2L}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Defining an initial spinor polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Psi_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 that respects the necessary BCs, 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Defining an initial polynomial that respects the necessary BCs in 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\pm\frac{L}{2}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi_{0}\left(y\right)=N_{0}\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
-\frac{2y}{L}
\end{array}\right],
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Psi_{0}\left(y\right) & =N_{0}\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
-\frac{2y}{L}
\end{array}\right],
\end{align*}

\end_inset

the valence-band will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Phi_{0}=\sigma_{x}\cdot\Psi_{0}^{*}.
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The simplest function that respects these BCs in the region 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\left[-\frac{L}{2},\frac{L}{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi_{0}\left(y\right)=N_{0}\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
-\frac{y}{L/2}
\end{array}\right],
\]

\end_inset

with its valence-band equivalent being 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{x}\cdot\Psi_{0}^{*}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The G-S process for higher order functions is the same, with the only caveat
 being the necessity of orthogonalizing the polynomials of the two bands.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Integrating the Hamiltonian matrix, we obtain the eigenvalues (left) and
 eigenfunctions (right, first conduction-band eigenfunction) for the basis
